{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486662"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:40:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:40:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"154"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/154"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.04,0.07,0.76,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"154"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92397"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/154"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"154"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75706"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"212"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31576"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31578"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42004"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92397"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents with a two-day history of headache that started over his right temple and is now a severe dull ache affecting his whole head. The pain does not radiate elsewhere and does not affect his neck. He has been trying to avoid bright lights and loud sounds since they exacerbate the headache. Paracetamol and aspirin have failed to alleviate the pain. He does not notice any visual changes but has felt nauseated. He has a history of tension headaches which are attributed to the large amount of coffee he consumes but says this headache feels different and much worse than previous headaches.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Meningitis","Tension headache","Space occupying lesion","Migraine headache","Cluster headache"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is most likely to be a \u003Cstrong\u003Emigraine headache\u003C/strong\u003E. Migraines\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eare common throbbing or pulsating headaches that are frequently accompanied by photophobia, phonophobia, nausea and vomiting. Pain is usually unilateral but may be bilateral. Sometimes episodes are preceded by an aura involving focal neurological symptoms. Analgesics like aspirin and paracetamol will only provide symptomatic relief in about 50% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeningitis\u003C/strong\u003E can also present with photophobia and phonophobia but would be more likely if the patient had a viral prodrome, fever, neck stiffness, and/or changes in mental state. \u003Cstrong\u003ETension headaches\u003C/strong\u003E present as a bilateral band-like tightness or pain that is exacerbated by stress, anxiety or sleep deprivation, though it does not typically feature photophobia or phonophobia. \u003Cstrong\u003ECluster headaches\u003C/strong\u003E are unilateral periorbital or temporal headaches that occur as short-lived, recurring attacks, sometimes accompanied with autonomic symptoms such as lacrimation or rhinorrhoea. Finally, \u003Cstrong\u003Espace-occupying lesions\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present as a chronic, progressive headache with focal neurological deficits, altered mental state or signs of increased intracranial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Migraines can be associated with photophobia, phonophobia, nausea and focal neurological symptoms"],"references":["Clinch CR. Evaluation of acute headaches in adults. Am Fam Physician. 2001;63(4):685-92."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75706"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"154"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75706"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-17T16:15:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-17T16:15:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"154"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92397"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"